snippet.textDisplay: Wise up people, the electronics in your machines lasts 15 years tops, the manufacturer supports the electronics for a maximum 12 years, unless you are able to have access to the software and port it to another processor in the future - your machine is scrap. The diagnostics is a halfway point, to have an open source operating system for all farm machinery is the requirement you need to keep your investment valuable after 10 years - otherwise write it down to $0.00 at the 10 year point. As an example I drive a fuel injected computerised car which is 25 years old but has an open source fuel injection computer running it. No electronic modules are available any longer for this (GM) car, but my car is worth more than an original........

snippet.textDisplay: Farm equipment manufacturers are doing the same thing which car manufacturers and dealers have gotten away with for decades. Right to repair acts have been proposed for years and keep getting canned by lobbyists representing manufacturers and the politicians in their pockets. It really is time to ban or limit lobbying and mandate equal public access to our elected officials. It is also time for the public rams a right to repair act right down the throats of manufacturers and dealers. Once a product is sold, it becomes the property of its purchaser. The only exception should be the ability to copy and sell the copies to others. If this is not done, the public will rightfully create its own market for aftermarket fixes to products which are too cumbersome or expensive to repair at the dealer or no longer supported. Vehicles and industrial equipment are way too expensive to treat as disposable or otherwise hold the purchaser hostage to insane repair costs.

snippet.textDisplay: This is far beyond a John Deere problem, a farmer problem, or an auto industry problem. The infiltration of "technology" into products over time, like the gentleman said, "since the 1990's," for the purposes of comfort, convenience, eco-friendliness (don't get me started), increased productivity, and claimed simplification to diagnose issues in a system, have all made us a throwaway culture. Refrigerators that once had automatic icemakers now have that icemaker, the LED lights inside, the thermostats, the zonal temp controls, and hell, the touch screen internet connected control panels and inventory lists, all run through a processor board. If it fires, and they do, your $2,000 fridge is useless. Look at HVAC systems in homes now....a lot of those are also affected by the outlawing of Freon.  It all comes down to often a mechanical part that is functioning fine, but a sensor that says otherwise, a parameter that is too narrow to allow functioning, and a computer board that is more fragile than a house of cards....without which nothing mechanical will work anymore.  To hold the customer captive is just wrong!

snippet.textDisplay: Back in the late 1980's and into the early 90's I was in the automotive industry, and the manufacturers were set on making autos a "dealer service only" vehicle. The diagnostic machines were priced at 25 thousand plus dollars, which made it unaffordable for independent shops. There were arguments by the big guys that diagnostic equipment could not be made cheaper, but after the independent shops & dealers brought a lawsuit against them, suddenly you could buy one off of the "tool truck" for a few hundred dollars. :O  Today, because of that lawsuit you can buy a code reader for as little as 25 bucks! ;)
